    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A naturally occurring dark brown earth pigment containing organic humus, peat, or coal material mixed with iron oxides, alumina and silica. When ignited, the pigment leaves a soft gray residue. The colorant is fugitive and fades on exposure to strong light. The pigment was first used in the 17th century; early sources were from the Cologne and Kassel regions of Germany, thus the alternate pigment names. The brown earth has since been obtained from various localities each of which may differ slightly in color and composition. To add to this confusion some pigments labeled "Van Dyck brown" were bituminous while others were synthetically made from from carbon black and iron oxide mixtures. For these synthetic mixtures, use "synthetic Van Dyck brown."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047822/MFA Conservation and Art Material Encyclopedia Online: CAMEO (2005-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一種天然產生的深棕土顏料，以有機腐殖質、泥炭或煤等材料混合氧化鐵、矽石和礬土而成。若經點燃，此顏料會產生軟性灰色殘渣。本著色劑暴露在強光下會褪色。范戴克棕首用於十七世紀，早期源自德國的科隆（Cologne）及卡塞爾（Kassel）地區，它們因此也成為此顏料的兩個別名。之後許多地方都開採此類棕土，但每種在顏色及成分上都有些微不同。更加複雜的是，有些標為「范戴克棕」的顏料為瀝青製成，其它則為碳黑和氧化鐵混合的合成物，此類合成混合物請稱「合成范戴克棕」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
